#: ../../../build_systems/makefilepackage.rst:-1
msgid ""
"A guide to using the Makefile build system in Spack for packages that use "
"plain Makefiles."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/makefilepackage.rst:13
msgid "Makefile"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/makefilepackage.rst:15
msgid ""
"The most primitive build system a package can use is a plain Makefile. "
"Makefiles are simple to write for small projects, but they usually require "
"you to edit the Makefile to set platform and compiler-specific variables."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/makefilepackage.rst:19
msgid "Phases"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/makefilepackage.rst:21
msgid ""
"The ``MakefileBuilder`` and ``MakefilePackage`` base classes come with 3 "
"phases:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/makefilepackage.rst:23
msgid "``edit`` - edit the Makefile"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/makefilepackage.rst:24
msgid "``build`` - build the project"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/makefilepackage.rst:25
msgid "``install`` - install the project"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/makefilepackage.rst:27
msgid ""
"By default, ``edit`` does nothing, but you can override it to replace "
"hardcoded Makefile variables. The ``build`` and ``install`` phases run:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/makefilepackage.rst:30
msgid ""
"$ make\n"
"$ make install"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/makefilepackage.rst:37
msgid "Important files"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/makefilepackage.rst:39
msgid ""
"The main file that matters for a ``MakefilePackage`` is the Makefile. This "
"file will be named one of the following ways:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/makefilepackage.rst:42
msgid "GNUmakefile (only works with GNU Make)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/makefilepackage.rst:43
msgid "Makefile (most common)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/makefilepackage.rst:44
msgid "makefile"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/makefilepackage.rst:46
msgid ""
"Some Makefiles also *include* other configuration files. Check for an "
"``include`` directive in the Makefile."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/makefilepackage.rst:50
msgid "Build system dependencies"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/makefilepackage.rst:52
msgid ""
"Spack assumes that the operating system will have a valid ``make`` utility "
"installed already, so you don't need to add a dependency on ``make``. "
"However, if the package uses a ``GNUmakefile`` or the developers recommend "
"using GNU Make, you should add a dependency on ``gmake``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/makefilepackage.rst:55
msgid "depends_on(\"gmake\", type=\"build\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/makefilepackage.rst:61
msgid "Types of Makefile packages"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/makefilepackage.rst:63
msgid ""
"Most of the work involved in packaging software that uses Makefiles involves "
"overriding or replacing hard-coded variables. Many packages make the mistake "
"of hard-coding compilers, usually for GCC or Intel. This is fine if you "
"happen to be using that particular compiler, but Spack is designed to work "
"with *any* compiler, and you need to ensure that this is the case."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/makefilepackage.rst:67
msgid ""
"Depending on how the Makefile is designed, there are 4 common strategies "
"that can be used to set or override the appropriate variables:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/makefilepackage.rst:70
msgid "Environment variables"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/makefilepackage.rst:72
msgid ""
"Make has multiple types of `assignment operators <https://www.gnu.org/"
"software/make/manual/make.html#Setting>`_. Some Makefiles use ``=`` to "
"assign variables. The only way to override these variables is to edit the "
"Makefile or override them on the command-line. However, Makefiles that use "
"``?=`` for assignment honor environment variables. Since Spack already sets "
"``CC``, ``CXX``, ``F77``, and ``FC``, you won't need to worry about setting "
"these variables. If there are any other variables you need to set, you can "
"do this in the ``setup_build_environment`` method:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/makefilepackage.rst:79
msgid ""
"def setup_build_environment(self, env: EnvironmentModifications) -> None:\n"
"    env.set(\"PREFIX\", prefix)\n"
"    env.set(\"BLASLIB\", spec[\"blas\"].libs.ld_flags)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/makefilepackage.rst:86
msgid ""
"`cbench <https://github.com/spack/spack-packages/blob/develop/repos/"
"spack_repo/builtin/packages/cbench/package.py>`_ is a good example of a "
"simple package that does this, while `esmf <https://github.com/spack/spack-"
"packages/blob/develop/repos/spack_repo/builtin/packages/esmf/package.py>`_ "
"is a good example of a more complex package."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/makefilepackage.rst:89
msgid "Command-line arguments"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/makefilepackage.rst:91
msgid ""
"If the Makefile ignores environment variables, the next thing to try is "
"command-line arguments. You can do this by overriding the ``build_targets`` "
"attribute. If you don't need access to the spec, you can do this like so:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/makefilepackage.rst:95
msgid "build_targets = [\"CC=cc\"]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/makefilepackage.rst:100
msgid "If you do need access to the spec, you can create a property like so:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/makefilepackage.rst:102
msgid ""
"@property\n"
"def build_targets(self):\n"
"    spec = self.spec\n"
"\n"
"    return [\n"
"        \"CC=cc\",\n"
"        f\"BLASLIB={spec['blas'].libs.ld_flags}\",\n"
"    ]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/makefilepackage.rst:114
msgid ""
"`cloverleaf <https://github.com/spack/spack-packages/blob/develop/repos/"
"spack_repo/builtin/packages/cloverleaf/package.py>`_ is a good example of a "
"package that uses this strategy."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/makefilepackage.rst:117
msgid "Edit Makefile"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/makefilepackage.rst:119
msgid ""
"Some Makefiles are just plain stubborn and will ignore command-line "
"variables. The only way to ensure that these packages build correctly is to "
"directly edit the Makefile. Spack provides a ``FileFilter`` class and a "
"``filter`` method to help with this. For example:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/makefilepackage.rst:124
msgid ""
"def edit(self, spec, prefix):\n"
"    makefile = FileFilter(\"Makefile\")\n"
"\n"
"    makefile.filter(r\"^\\s*CC\\s*=.*\", f\"CC = {spack_cc}\")\n"
"    makefile.filter(r\"^\\s*CXX\\s*=.*\", f\"CXX = {spack_cxx}\")\n"
"    makefile.filter(r\"^\\s*F77\\s*=.*\", f\"F77 = {spack_f77}\")\n"
"    makefile.filter(r\"^\\s*FC\\s*=.*\", f\"FC = {spack_fc}\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/makefilepackage.rst:135
msgid ""
"`stream <https://github.com/spack/spack-packages/blob/develop/repos/"
"spack_repo/builtin/packages/stream/package.py>`_ is a good example of a "
"package that involves editing a Makefile to set the appropriate variables."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/makefilepackage.rst:138
msgid "Config file"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/makefilepackage.rst:140
msgid ""
"More complex packages often involve Makefiles that *include* a configuration "
"file. These configuration files are primarily composed of variables relating "
"to the compiler, platform, and the location of dependencies or names of "
"libraries. Since these config files are dependent on the compiler and "
"platform, you will often see entire directories of examples for common "
"compilers and architectures. Use these examples to help determine what "
"possible values to use."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/makefilepackage.rst:145
msgid ""
"If the config file is long and only contains one or two variables that need "
"to be modified, you can use the technique above to edit the config file. "
"However, if you end up needing to modify most of the variables, it may be "
"easier to write a new file from scratch."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/makefilepackage.rst:148
msgid ""
"If each variable is independent of each other, a dictionary works well for "
"storing variables:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/makefilepackage.rst:150
msgid ""
"def edit(self, spec, prefix):\n"
"    config = {\n"
"        \"CC\": \"cc\",\n"
"        \"MAKE\": \"make\",\n"
"    }\n"
"\n"
"    if spec.satisfies(\"+blas\"):\n"
"        config[\"BLAS_LIBS\"] = spec[\"blas\"].libs.joined()\n"
"\n"
"    with open(\"make.inc\", \"w\") as inc:\n"
"        for key in config:\n"
"            inc.write(f\"{key} = {config[key]}\\n\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/makefilepackage.rst:166
msgid ""
"`elk <https://github.com/spack/spack-packages/blob/develop/repos/spack_repo/"
"builtin/packages/elk/package.py>`_ is a good example of a package that uses "
"a dictionary to store configuration variables."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/makefilepackage.rst:168
msgid ""
"If the order of variables is important, it may be easier to store them in a "
"list:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/makefilepackage.rst:170
msgid ""
"def edit(self, spec, prefix):\n"
"    config = [\n"
"        f\"INSTALL_DIR = {prefix}\",\n"
"        \"INCLUDE_DIR = $(INSTALL_DIR)/include\",\n"
"        \"LIBRARY_DIR = $(INSTALL_DIR)/lib\",\n"
"    ]\n"
"\n"
"    with open(\"make.inc\", \"w\") as inc:\n"
"        for var in config:\n"
"            inc.write(f\"{var}\\n\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/makefilepackage.rst:184
msgid ""
"`hpl <https://github.com/spack/spack-packages/blob/develop/repos/spack_repo/"
"builtin/packages/hpl/package.py>`_ is a good example of a package that uses "
"a list to store configuration variables."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/makefilepackage.rst:187
msgid "Variables to watch out for"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/makefilepackage.rst:189
msgid ""
"The following is a list of common variables to watch out for. The first two "
"sections are `implicit variables <https://www.gnu.org/software/make/manual/"
"html_node/Implicit-Variables.html>`_ defined by Make and will always use the "
"same name, while the rest are user-defined variables and may vary from "
"package to package."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/makefilepackage.rst:192
msgid "**Compilers**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/makefilepackage.rst:194
msgid ""
"This includes variables such as ``CC``, ``CXX``, ``F77``, ``F90``, and "
"``FC``, as well as variables related to MPI compiler wrappers, like "
"``MPICC`` and friends."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/makefilepackage.rst:196
msgid "**Compiler flags**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/makefilepackage.rst:198
msgid ""
"This includes variables for compiler flags, such as ``CFLAGS``, "
"``CXXFLAGS``, ``F77FLAGS``, ``F90FLAGS``, ``FCFLAGS``, and ``CPPFLAGS``. "
"These variables are often hard-coded to contain flags specific to a certain "
"compiler. If these flags don't work for every compiler, you may want to "
"consider filtering them."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/makefilepackage.rst:202
msgid "**Variables that enable or disable features**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/makefilepackage.rst:204
msgid ""
"This includes variables like ``MPI``, ``OPENMP``, ``PIC``, and ``DEBUG``. "
"These flags often require you to create a variant so that you can either "
"build with or without MPI support, for example. These flags are often "
"compiler-dependent. You should replace them with the appropriate compiler "
"flags, such as ``self.compiler.openmp_flag`` or ``self.compiler.pic_flag``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/makefilepackage.rst:209
msgid "**Platform flags**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/makefilepackage.rst:211
msgid ""
"These flags control the type of architecture that the executable is compiled "
"for. Watch out for variables like ``PLAT`` or ``ARCH``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/makefilepackage.rst:214
msgid "**Dependencies**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/makefilepackage.rst:216
msgid ""
"Look out for variables that sound like they could be used to locate "
"dependencies, such as ``JAVA_HOME``, ``JPEG_ROOT``, or ``ZLIBDIR``. Also "
"watch out for variables that control linking, such as ``LIBS``, ``LDFLAGS``, "
"and ``INCLUDES``. These variables need to be set to the installation prefix "
"of a dependency, or to the correct linker flags to link to that dependency."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/makefilepackage.rst:220
msgid "**Installation prefix**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/makefilepackage.rst:222
msgid ""
"If your Makefile has an ``install`` target, it needs some way of knowing "
"where to install. By default, many packages install to ``/usr`` or ``/usr/"
"local``. Since many Spack users won't have sudo privileges, it is imperative "
"that each package is installed to the proper prefix. Look for variables like "
"``PREFIX`` or ``INSTALL``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/makefilepackage.rst:228
msgid "Makefiles in a sub-directory"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/makefilepackage.rst:230
msgid ""
"Not every package places their Makefile in the root of the package tarball. "
"If the Makefile is in a sub-directory like ``src``, you can tell Spack where "
"to locate it like so:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/makefilepackage.rst:233
msgid "build_directory = \"src\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/makefilepackage.rst:239
msgid "Manual installation"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/makefilepackage.rst:241
msgid ""
"Not every Makefile includes an ``install`` target. If this is the case, you "
"can override the default ``install`` method to manually install the package:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/makefilepackage.rst:244
msgid ""
"def install(self, spec, prefix):\n"
"    mkdir(prefix.bin)\n"
"    install(\"foo\", prefix.bin)\n"
"    install_tree(\"lib\", prefix.lib)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/makefilepackage.rst:253
msgid "External documentation"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/makefilepackage.rst:255
msgid ""
"For more information on reading and writing Makefiles, see: https://www.gnu."
"org/software/make/manual/make.html"
msgstr ""
